[Individual cases and outbreaks of HFMD occur worldwide. In temperate
climates, cases occur more often in summer and early autumn. HFMD
caused by coxsackievirus A16 infection is generally a mild disease,
with nearly all patients recovering in 7 to 10 days without medical
treatment.

Since 1997, however, outbreaks of HFMD caused by enterovirus 71 have
been reported in Asia and Australia. HFMD caused by enterovirus 71 has
shown a higher incidence of neurologic involvement, and fatal cases of
encephalitis have occurred during outbreaks. However, such serious
outcomes are still very rare.

HFMD infection is spread from person to person by direct contact.
Infectious virus is found in the nose and throat secretions, saliva,
blister fluid and stool of infected persons. The virus is most often
spread by persons with unwashed, virus-contaminated hands and by
contact with virus-contaminated surfaces. Infected persons are most
contagious during the 1st week of the illness, but may remain a source
of infection for others after symptoms have resolved. Complications
from virus infections that cause HFMD are uncommon; "aseptic"
meningitis can occur rarely with HFMD, causing fever, headache, stiff
neck, or back pain. Some patients may require hospitalization for a
short time. Other more serious conditions, such as encephalitis, are
very rare although encephalitis can be fatal.

Further information about HFMD can be obtained from the CDC website
at http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvrd/revb/enterovirus/hfhf.htm. -
Mod.CP]
